column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: While making a delivery to the Shell Station 37 Birch St (Rt28) Derry, NH, driver had two hoses each connected to a pocket valve on the tanker trailer. One hose was connected to the fitting on the fill pipe and the other hose was not connected and laying on the ground. Driver opened wrong valve believing he opened the pocket to the connected hose however, opened to the hose which was not connected. Upon hearing splash, driver immediately closed valve and deploying spill kit contained spill on the concrete pad and surrounding asphalt. No product entered sewer or outfalls. Emergency reponse was provided and environmental contractor cleaned up spill. New Hampshire Department of Environmental Services was on scene and satified with response.
column169: Driver issued discpline and will receive remeidial training is proper delivery procedures.

column163: Hwy 73, 3.5 Miles W of Taylor Bayou
column168: A driver found a slight drip coming from the bottom of the van that he was moving from the 10 day yard to our dolly down yard.  The van was Rinchem #D5300A and the load was from Monomonee.  The drip was contained on the van and was brought straight to the CSB unloading bay.  The leak was again contained at the CSB unloading bay.  After several pallets were removed from the van, the leaking container was identified.  The drum was a 55 gallon DM and appeared to have a pinhole in the very bottom of the drum.  The drum was Line 02 on manifest #0257541VES.  The drum was overpacked and the cleanup of the area where the spill occurred on the van began.  The area was triple rinsed with diesel and dried with hidry after each rinse.  A wipe test will be performed on the affected area of the van.  The affected area at the 10 day yard will be excavated and a sample will be taken.  Wipe test and sample results to follow.

column168: The shipment was offered to Hapag-Lloyd from New Orleans, Louisiana on the Bonn Express to Rotterdam, Netherlands as non-hazardous cargo.    The shipper advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel sailed from New Orleans of undeclared hazardous material loaded in the container.    The shipping papers that accompanied the container did not indicate the presence of hazardous materials, and the container was not placarded and/or marked.    The shipper subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.    Hapag-Lloyd advised the Master of the vessel of the undeclared hazardous materials onboard.

column168: A BNSF switch crew working an inbound BNSF train in the railyard, reported ADMX 30628 ( DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product from the top fitting area. ADMX 30628 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard with absorbent material placed under it. The shipper was contacted and a mobile tank car repair unit was dispatched to inspect and/or repair ADMX 30628. The repair responder reported finding the liquid valve's valve handle stem with a loose packing retainer nut. Responder secured this retainer nut by 1545 hrs. PDT, 5/05/08, eliminating any further product release. Spillage evaporated.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A FRA hazardous material inspector reported that DBUX 300123 ( DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was observed in the railyard with a fresh product stain on its side shell. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected DBUX 300123 finding the liquid valve loose (two turns loose) on its threaded base. Responder secured this liquid valve by 1730 hrs. PDT, 5/01/08, thus eliminating further product release. The responder also noted that this valve's long handle had to be precisely positioned to allow the valve protective housing cover to properly close. Non-evaporating spillage was wiped. No ground impact from this product release was evident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: I John Vergis, Assistant Environmental Officer for the Wheeling and Lake Erie Railway, was called at about 1230 on 5-2-08 by our car inspector in Canton, Ohio.  When he called he said that he was inspecting cars so they could be put into Marathon Oil for loadig.  When inspecting these cars he noticed a gas odor coming from this car.  He called me and I was on the scene in about 15 minutes.  I inspected the car and determined that the PRD was leaking a small amount of vapor.  I tried to reset the spring loaded valve by tapping on it with a brass hammer and the valve would not seal.  I eneded up taking the PRD apart and replaced the two O rings that were inside.  When reinstalled I checked again for leaks and the leak was repaired.  The car was then released to go back to Marathon for loading. I have no way of knowing how long the car leaked.

The tank was then pulled back onto Chemtrade's loading/containment area, where a 5 gallon bucket was placed under the leaking rib of the trailer. The tank was leaking through a weep hole in a rib towards the back third of the trailer. The contents of the tank were offloaded onto a standby trailer. column168: At approximately 5:00 pm a loader was trying to change out pump PM-4888 because he was unable to get a green light on the meter open. When he disconnected the dry disconnect hose from the railcar fitting, approximately 5-7 gallons of Ethanol spilled from the railcar product fitting. The railcar adapter must have stuck open slightly. The Ethanol evaporated. No Ethanol left the asphalt containment area.
column169: The railcar adapter was immediately removed from service and tagged "Do Not Use". Loaders will also be made aware that they should always ensure the railcar valve is in the closed position prior to disconnecting the dry disconnect fitting.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  During a routine inspection, the driver discovered a small amount of free product on the bumper of the trailer. Upon further investigation it was discovered that one (1) 55-gallon drum was leaking, as a result of the load shifting.  Advanced Environmental Solutions of Belen, New Mexico was dispatched to perform the cleanup.     Advanced Environmental Solutions investigated the trailer, and discovered that all of the free liquid hardened.  Advanced Environmental Solutions applied absorbent material inside of the trailer, as a precautionary measure, and placed the leaking drum into an 85-gallon overpack drum.  The drum was left on the trailer and the trailer continued to its final destination.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, Roadrunner Dawes Freight Systems, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: On 05/08/08 at 08:52 hours, at the CSX Transportation Yard in Port Huron, MI a CSX Transportation Mechanical Department Inspector reported a hissing sound from AMOX 33763, a tank car containing the residue of liquefied petroleum gas. CSXT Transportation contacted the consignee and a represenataive from Oil Well Supply Company responded. They reported a vapor leak at the vapor line valve due to the valve being slightly open and the plug for the valve not being tool tight. They secured the valve and its plug and the leak ceased. They reported two turns were made to this plug to secure it tool tight and that the same was done to the plugs for the liquid line valves.  5(4 + 5 + 0) x (2 + 0) = 90  NARRI Cause Code 136

column168: A mixture of waste petroleum distillates, methanol, acetone, water, acetonitrile, and xylene leaked from a ten gallon shipping container as a result of what appeared to be a failure of the drum’s structural integrity.  Of the original 9 gallons within the container, Triumvirate’s spill response personnel estimate that approximately 4 gallons of the original contents of the drum leaked out while the drum was in transit.    At approximately 18:15, when the vehicle arrived at a refueling station after a hazardous waste pickup, Triumvirate personnel observed that a small trickle of liquid was dripping from the front corner of the box truck.   Triumvirate staff members ascertained the potential hazards in the back of the truck by examining the hazardous waste manifest, donned Level C personal protection equipment, and climbed in to the rear of the truck to identify the source of the liquid.  The leaking container was quickly identified: a reconditioned steel waste container (1A1/X1.4/250/06/USA/SDCC), one drum of the two that were shipped.  The leaking drum had been securely stacked for shipment atop the other identical, non-leaking container.    Upon inspection, a stream of liquid was clearly flowing from a small “pinhole” leak in the underside of the drum along the seam, directly adjacent to the lip.   The drum was lifted and deposited into a larger 30 gallon open head, steel drum to contain the leak. All other drums and materials on the truck where removed and all surfaces that had come into contact with the free liquid where decontaminated with rags and biodegradable cleaning material. The floor surface of the box truck was decontaminated in the same manner, using rags and the same cleaning material. The spill response team confirmed that no other container in the truck was leaking.    Triumvirate staff verified that the waste container did not show any signs of leakage at the time that the container was loaded on to the truck, at approximately 16:45.  Concluding that the leak must have begun during transit, the responders began to inspect the truck for any possible causes of the leak.  No sharp protrusions in the truck were detected, nor were the responders able to determine that the container held any incompatible materials that may have corroded the drum.  Unable to clearly identify the cause of the leak, Triumvirate staff conjectured that the reconditioned container’s integrity had become weakened at some point and began to leak at the weakest spot of the container (the seam on the underside) during the stresses of transportation.
column169: Recommendations  Triumvirate Environmental takes great efforts to purchase and supply only high quality waste containers, but occasionally hazardous waste generators offer their own waste containers for shipment on Triumvirate trucks.  Triumvirate employees are instructed to verify that all hazardous waste containers bear DOT-approved markings prior to shipment, but Triumvirate shall instruct employees to more thoroughly inspect any waste containers that Triumvirate Environmental has not supplied.    The offeror of this waste was notified of the situation and asked by Triumvirate to inspect their shipping container inventory for any potential defects.  Triumvirate also asked the offeror to re-evaluate their selection process for selecting proper shipping containers.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was enroute to the intended waste management facility when the driver stopped to conduct a routine load check.  Upon inspecting the trailer, the driver noticed that a clear liquid began to drip from the rear door of the trailer.  The driver immedialtey activated Clean Harbors' internal emergency reponse plan by securing the scene, placeing a suitable absorbent material under the leak and contacting Clean Harbor's 24-hour emergency reponse operators.  Upon this notification, a response team was assembled and dispacthed to the scene.  In addition, a telephonic report was made to the Illinois Emergency Management Agency (Report # H008-0644) advising them of the release and the corrective actions being taken.    Upon arrival to the scene, the response team identified the leaking containerand removed those containers necessary to remediate the scene.  The leaking container was immedialtey placed into a suitable salvage drum along with all clean up materials (absorbants and cleaning solution used to decontaminate the trailer and concret parking area) and secured from transportation.  Once the trailer and parking area was cleaned, the trailer was reloaded and the vehicle departed to the intended waste management facility.  The response activity was conducted without inciodent and there were no injuries as a result of this incident.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, loading personnel have been reinstructed to inspect all pallets used to consolidate non-bulk packages for shipment and have been instructed to either dispose of damaged pllets or remove them until proper repairs are made to preclude a similar incident.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported CITX 221074 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product from the top fitting area in the railyard. CITX 221074 was carefully moved to and over the containment pit in the railyard. BNSF contract responders reported finding the T-handled sample line valve open with the closure plug not applied. Responders closed this valve and applied the plug, stopping further product release by 2330 hrs. CDT, 5/02/08. All seals were intact and all other top fittings were found to be secure. No ground impact from this product release outside the containment area was evident. Some product spillage ran down the sides of CITX 221074 into the containment area which had standing water from a previous rain event. Samples of the liquid in the containment pit were sent to a laboratory for analysis to assist in proper disposal of this mixture. Spillage on the side shell of CITX 221074 evaporated.

column168: ACFX 84808 (DOT 111A60W tank car) was reported in the railyard dripping product from the A-end tank area. A BNSF contract responder observed the product within seeping out from under the outer insulation jacket at the A-end of this tank car. Wooden plugs were inserted into the jacketed seams to ebb the flow of the product seepage. ACFX 84808 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. Heavy duty polyethylene sheeting was placed under ACFX 84808 to catch product drippings. Sand was applied to all ground impact areas. Additional plugs were inserted to stop the flow of the product release. The source of the tank shell compromise was not ascertained due to the jacketing over the shell. Afterwards, when it was safe to move, ACFX 84808 was moved to the nearby consignee location for unloading. On Monday, 5/12/08, the solidified asphalt spillage was excavated and disposed of at the consignee facility.

column168: RCRX 1244 (DOT 111A100W5 tank car) was reported in the railyard with residue product vapor emanating from its top fitting area. RCRX 1244 was cordoned off. The local F.D. and the county HAZMAT Response team responded. These responders tightened the three flange bolts at the base of the rupture disc housing assembly, which greatly reduced the vapor emissions. A BNSF contract responder arrived at the scene around midnight and after a briefing the county response team, the contract responder completely tool tightened the three flange bolts at the base of the rupture disc housing assembly by 0030 hrs. CDT, 5/09/08. No liquid product was released, only residue product vapors. After this securement was completed, the residue product vapor release ceased. All valve assemblies and other top fittings were neutralized and water rinsed. RCRX 1244 continued to be monitored and after no further vapor release was observed; RCRX 1244 was released to proceed to its destination.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: An outbound driver reported intermodal tank container EXFU 380118 (IM101 tank container) for export in the intermodal parking lot dripping product from the end discharge valve. Shipper contract responders inspected EXFU 380118 observing a very small pool of liquid under the discharge valve's safety/dust cap. This valve's (foot) handle was exercised and cycled to ensure that it was closing the valve fully. The valve's safety cap was slowing unscrewed. A small amount of product was found inside the cap. The cap and the valve were wiped clean. All ground spillage was also wiped. Teflon tape was applied to all threaded areas and the safety cap was applied and tool tightened. No further product drips were observed afterwards. Inspection also revealed that the top hatchway was not fully secured. Two of the eight swing bolts were not applied and hanging down. The responders applied the loose swing bolts and tightened all swing bolts with their corresponding wing nuts. Also, one placard was missing on the left side of EXFU 380118 and a new Flammable Liquid placard was applied. The shipper was notified to reinspect EXFU 380118 to ensure that the discharge valve was working properly. A shipper contract mechanical responder later advised that all repairs were completed and EXFU 380118 was out-gated.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: CLean Harbors Environmental Services arrived at a shipper's loction to load dissolved air floatation float generated by the refinery industry.  At the comclusion of the loading process, the equipment operator shut the valve on the storage tank and the valve on the cargo tank after bleeding hose used to transfer the material.  During this operation, it was discoverd that the scrubber unit associated with the pump used to load the material had overfilled and allowed a small amount of material to escape from the exhaust stack of the scrubber system.  Approximatley 1 quart of material was released onto the side of the tank and the fender of the vehicle.  The equipment operator immediatley turned the pump off and used absorbent pads to collect the material that had escaped.  He then proceeded to drain the scrubber unit and placed this residual material into the tank.  The absorbant pads were containerized and placed into storage pending disposal to a licensed waste management facility.
column169: AN investigation into the release determined that the material being loaded has a tendency to foam during the loadig process.  As this material is loaded using a mechanical pump, the scrubber system used in conjunction with the pump migrated from the scrubber's exhaust tank and escaped from the exhaust stack.  It was determined that the release would have been prevented had the equipment operator inspected and drained the scrubber system on a more frequent basis while the loading operation was being performed.  In order to prevent a recurrence, a step-by step proccedure has been developed  for this product stream that oulines the steps needed to be taken to insure appropriate steps are taken during the loaidng process to prevent the build-up of excess foam in the scrubber system. This procedure will then be reviewed with each driver supporting this project.

column168: WHILE PREFROMING A DAILY INSPECTION OF THE TRAILERS AT VEOLIA'S 10-DAY TRANSFER FACILITY LOCATED IN PHILADELPHIA, PA, A VEOLIA EMPLOYEE NOTICED MATERIAL DRIPPING FROM A TRAILER ONTO THE PAVED PARKING LOT. THE AMOUNT OF MATERIAL RELEASED TO THE GROUND TOTALLED APPROXIMATELY 1-2 GALLONS. ALL DRUMS WERE REMOVED FROM THE TRUCK AND THE LEAKING 55 GALLON POLY DRUM WAS OVERPACKED INTO AN 85 GALLON POLY OVERPACK. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY TRAINED VEOLIA HAZMAT EMPLOYEES USING SPEEDI DRI AND THE MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO A DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.  THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER WAS ALSO CLEANED WITH SPEEDI DRI AND PLACED INTO THE DRUM FOR DISPOSAL. THE TOTAL AMOUNT RELEASE WAS APX 3-4 GALLONS OF STYRENE MONOMER. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE PAVED PARKING LOT AND THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER. THERE WAS NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT TO THE SURROUNDING AREA.
column169: AFTER THOROUGH INVESTIGATION, IT WAS IDENTIFIED THAT THE DRUM MAY HAVE BEEN DAMAGED BY LOADING ONTO THE TRAILER WITH THE FORKLIFT, BUT UNCERTAIN OF THIS AT THIS TIME. THE TOP CHIME OF THE POLY DRUM WAS DAMAGED/CRACKED WHICH COULD HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY THE FORKLIFT DRUM ATTACHMENT DURING LOADING OR UNLOADING. VEOLIA HAS STRESSED TO THE FACILITY EMPLOYEES ABOUT THE IMPORTANCE OF PROPER DRUM HANDELING TECHNIQUES FOR LOADING AND UNLOADING PACKAGES.

column168: On May 21,2008 at 17:53, personnel in the CSXT Tilford Yard discovered ACFX84123, a loaded tank car of Ethanol Solutions, leaking from the top of the car.  The area around the rail car was isolated and Chemtrec (report number 2008-05-21-00247) assisted in contacting the shipper, Equistar Chemicals.  Hepaco, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the connection of the threaded liquid line valve to the tank car less than tool tight. Contractor personnel removed the valve, added teflon tape to the threaded connection, then reinstalled the fitting and properly secured the valve body tool tight.  Since the car no longer complied with DOT specifications, the shipper, Equistar, applied for a FRA Movement Approval.  Upon receiving notice of approval (FRA-08050158) the car was released to destination. Approximately 10 gallons was released from the container.  Cause Code: 282  NARRI = 5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80

column168: A BNSF mechanical carman reported TILX 290442 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) being switched in the railyard (after arrival from an inbound BNSF train) with a product slosh from the manway area. TILX 290442 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting detailed inspection. No product release was observed when TILX 290442 was not moving. After inspection, a shipper responder reported that the manway nozzle gasket was not applied. All manway securement bolts were found to be tool tight, but without a good gasket seal, the product within escaped between the manway lid and the manway nozzle joint during movement. The responder applied the manway nozzle gasket, closed the manway lid and tool tightened all six manway securement bolts. All spillage around the manway nozzle evaporated. Securement was completed at approximately 1500 hrs. PDT, 5/14/08.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Driver was transferring product from cargo tank to customer storage tank.  The consignee did not have room for all of the product in the storage tank.  Hence, driver was not able to clear his hose properly.  Fill line connection was 4 feet in the air.  Driver was unprepared for the amount of product that came out of the bleeder valve at trailer before he disconnected the hose and product that was in the line overflowed the bucket.  Customer hosed it to their containment drain.
column169: It's difficult to clear the line when there is still product in the trailer but the driver should have been prepared by slowly opening the bleeder valve to control the flow.

column62: Missing Component or Device; Valve Open
column168: A BNSF switch crew reported DBUX 300200 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) sloshing product from the top fitting area during switching movement in the railyard. Switching was stopped and DBUX 300200 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. No product was observed being expelled when DBUX 300200 was standing still. BNSF contract responders inspected DBUX 300200 and reported finding the vapor valve in the open position and its one inch closure plug not applied. This open orifice allowed the product within DBUX 300200 to escape during switching movement in the railyard. The responder closed the valve, applied and tool tightened the closure plug. Also, four of the eight manway securement bolts were found to be less than tool tight; and the responder tool tightened these loose manway securement bolts. The visible spillage atop DBUX 300200 was wiped and no ground impact was evident. Response was concluded by approximately 0900 hrs. CDT, 5/21/08.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On Monday, May 26, 2008 at 1425 hours A-C-T was notified by Landstar Systems of a Sodium Hydroxide spill at a Pilot Truck Stop at 2015 Antonio Street  (I-10, Exit 0) in Anthony, Texas. Due to a possible load shift, one (1) 275-gallon tote of Stabrom 909 Biocide (UN3266) developed a pinhole leak approximately 5-8 inches below the top of the tote.  This released approximately 25 gallons of product onto the trailer floor, parking area and soil shoulder of the parking area.    An emergency response team was dispatched to the site.  Upon arrival at the site, the response team was able to stop the leak by plugging the pinhole with a plug & dike product.  The response team applied granular sorbents to clean up the impacted areas of the roadway and trailer.  All totes were removed from the trailer, placed on plastic and decontaminated.  Once the totes were decontaminated they were reloaded into the trailer.  The load was properly blocked and braced for transport.   The response then excavated approximately 4 yards of impacted soil.  All waste was disposed at a permitted facility
column169: Due to a possable load shift being the cause of this event, better blocking and braceing should be completed prior to transport.  Additionally, the load should be doubled check to be assured that is is stable for tansport.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: On May 25, 2008 at 17:15, personnel in the CSXT Cumberland Yard discovered a loaded tank car of gasoline leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the Cumberland Fire Department, Epic Aviation, Maryland Department of Environment (report# 17988) and Chemtrec (Report # 2005052500075) were notified. A CSXT General Car Foreman (Hazmat Sentinel Plus) and the Cumberland Fire Department found the liquid valve slighlty open and the liquid line plug less than tool tight. The liquid valve was closed and the plug was made tool tight. The car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.  Cause Code: 249  NARRI:  5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80
column169: No additional comments.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On 05/23/08 at 17:00, personnel in the CSXT Kayne Avenue Rail yard discovered GATX 79786, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, NOS, leaking from the two pressure relief devices on the top of the rail car. The car was moved to track 09 where it was isolated. A CSXT response contractor was dispatched to the scene and found the car to be overloaded. 700 Gallons were removed from the rail car and loaded into the response contractors vacuum truck. The car was resealed and sent to destination for unloading.     NARRI :  5 (5+3+0) * (2+0) = 80  Cause Code = 419, NAR points =5
column169: No additional comments.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling on Interstate 405 southbound, approximately 1/2 mile south of Venture Boulevard, a leak was discovered coming from the tanker.  Upon further investigation it was discovered that the release was the result of a loose dome lid.  Approximately 5 gallons of free product were released and impacted the tanker and asphalt.  The Los Angeles Fire Department and CALTRANS responded to assess the site. CALTRANS performed the cleanup of the impacted tanker and asphalt.  CALTRANS will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the incident.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, California Tank Lines, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: On May 29, 2008 at 09:00, personnel in the CSXT Barr Yard were alerted via the FRA that TILX 401199, a loaded tank car of carbon dioxide, refrigerated liquid, lwas eaking from the pressure plate. The car was isolated and the shipper, local, state and/or federal agencies were notified (CHEMTREC was not nitified due to direct contact with both Shipper and car owners Air Liquide). Eagle construction, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene. The car was traveling on a one time movement approval and was inadvertantly loaded in violation of the approval. The car was tracked to CSX yard where the car was bad ordered and staged for transload. This incident did require a special switching move.      Cause Code: 221  NARRI:  5 (5+1+0) X (2+0) = 60

column168: Driver said that customer storage tank and sight gauge were brand new.  When he went to hook his hose up to the fill line, it was a little loose.  They fixed it but he was still concerned so he just cracked his valve open a little to start the transfer of product.  The fill line connection was okay but then product started to leak out of the ball valve for the sight glass which was cracked.  They tried to fix it but broke it off completely. Product was continuing to leak out of customer tank.  They couldn't stop if until it got below that level.  Product was going into a containment area and customer would handle cleanup.  It goes into their recovery system and not to any public sewer.
column169: The customer fixed the tank and sight glass so the driver was able to successfully offload the product.

column168: PREVIOUS TO THE DELIVERY TANK TESTING WAS PERFORMED ON THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK RECEIVING THE GASOLINE. AS THE TANK FILLED A COVER USED TO TEST THE TANK CAM OFF CAUSING THE GASOLINE TO LEAK OUT. THIS COVER WAS NOT INVOLVED IN THE DELIVERY PROCESS. THE LEAK LASTED APPROX. 3-5 SECONDS. AS SOON AS THE LEAK OCCURRED THE DRIVER CLOSED THE DELIVERY VALVE, CONTAINED AS MUCH OF THE SPILL AS POSSIBLE AND NOTIFIED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT. PERFORMANCE TANKS SENT A FIRST RESPONDER TO THE SITE TO CLEAN UP ANY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND REMEDIATE THE SITE, AT THIS TIME COST ESTIMATES ARE NOT AVAILABLE. NO VEHICLE RELATED EQUIPMENT WAS INVOLVED IN CAUSING THE SPILL.
column169: RECOMMENDED ADVISING THE TANK TEST CONTRACTOR TO INSTRUCT EMPLOYEES IN THE NECESSITY TO CHECK ALL WORK UPON COMPLETION.

column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence.  After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction.  For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: Employee was driving unit from one oil well location to another oil well location that was approximately 30 miles between locations. They were traveling in a convoy fashion and had to make a right turn from State Hwy 65N to County Rd, (E. Mountain). As the employee approached the turn onto the county road,he failed to realize that it required a wide swing out due to the ditch adjacent to the roadway and the narrow road to which they were turning. As the employee made the turn, the trailer was off the pavement and was going through the edge of the ditch, which was about 3 feet deep. As the employee noticed the trailer going through the ditch, he attempted to stop, at which time the loaded tanker began to lean and laid over in a slow motion roll. The contents of the tank began to leak slightly around one of the domes in the top of the tank. The members of the crew had been trained in Hazardous Materials Emergency Response in accordance with OSHA 29 CFR 191 0.120 (q)(6)(iii) HazWOPER. The crew quickly secured the dome and the result was a minimal release of 20 gallons of 15% HCL. The ditch in which the HCL was now in was diked and the product was contained. The supervisor on the scene immediately contacted the safety department and a emergency response clean-up contractor was dispatched to the scene. The scene was cleaned up in accordance with local, state and federal guidelines and the waste materials were properly disposed of through an approved hazardous waste disposal facility. The release appeared to be the result of the torque that had been applied to the tank as it rolled over and not to any design or container failure. The dome lid was slightly twisted which caused the leak. The crew tightened a couple of the bolts to the dome lid and stopped the leak. The product leakage was only a short duration
column169: We have implemented a program to ensure that all vehicles in the convoy are equipped with two-way radio communications and will be relaying details of the road conditions as we travel. We have also mandated that any employee driving a unit transporting Hazardous Materials must have a minimum of 1 year of service with the company and must be re-certified every three months to transport Hazardous Materials for the first year of their initial certification. We have a library of the road hazards, including tight turns, and will review the Road Hazard Assessments with the employees during training sessions.

column168: Shipment moved from Grand Rapids (GRR) to Chicago (ORD) as an export shipment. Freight (Ultra-light Helicopter)and an accompanying support kit (plywood box) was offered to Air France. Air France, on inspecting the shipment,rejected it for transportation saying they could smell fuel. Shipment was returned to Chicago's UPS Gateway where the shipment was checked for reasons which might cause a fuel smell. It was at this point, that the gate way employees discovered the Explosives in the plywood box, which was heavily shrink wrapped, thus preventing anyone from seeing inside of it. After speaking with the UPS GRR office, they stated that there was no smell of fuel at all.Additionally, they stated that there was no way to see inside the plywood box due to the use of Shrink Wrapping. This shipment also had a Shipper's Certification of Articles Not Restricted accompanying it.
column169: CORRECTIVE ACTIONS: 1. RETRAIN ENTIRE STAFF ON NEVER TO BY PASS THE SCULLY SYSTEM OR ANY SAFETY DEVICE. 2. ALL SCULLY SYSTEMS TO BE LOCKED OUT BY MANAGEMENT AND ONLY THE TERMINAL MANAGER WILL HAVE THE KEY. 3. NEVER LET ANYONE PRESSURE YOU TO PERFORM A DUTY OR SERVICE THAT IS UNSAFE OR TO BREAK A PROCEDURE. 4. WHEN DESIGNATED COMPARTMENT ON A TRAILER IS NOT TO BE LOADED, LEAVE THE 4" CAP ON THE COMPARTMENT, TO REMIND THE LOADER THAT THE COMPARTMENT IS NOT TO BE LOADED.5. TRANSFLO HAS REQUIRED ALL TRUCKING CARRIERS TO UP DATE THEIR TRAILER SCULLY SYSTEMS SO THAT THEY ARE COMPATIBLE WITH TRANSFLO' S SCULLY SYSTEMS.

column168: An OTVR (Otter Tail Valley RR) crew delivering interchange rail cars to the BNSF railyard reported that entrained UTLX 210936 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car to be interchanged) was leaking product from the top of this tank car. The local F.D. responded and reported that the liquid valve handle was loose with this valve partially open. The valve was closed and the valve stem handle's retaining nut was tightened. The liquid valve was secured by 1643 hrs. CDT, 5/14/08. Afterwards, BNSF contract responders inspected UTLX 210936 and confirmed that the product outage level was appropriate and all the valves and fittings were properly secured. The contract responders also replaced all seals that were broken or disturbed by the F.D. responders. The ballast and ground area were sampled and no product pooling or ground impact was evident. All spillage evaporated.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A BNSF locomotive hostler crew reported UTLX 210932 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the railyard was leaking product from the top of this tank car. Afterwards, BNSF contract responders inspected UTLX 210932 at Dilworth, MN and confirmed that the product outage level was appropriate and all the valves and fittings were properly secured. The contract responders also replaced all seals that were broken or disturbed by the F.D. responders.

column168: Driver was using product pump to offload 1000 gal from cargo tank to the customers  1800 gallon storage tank that had 600 in it to start.  Some product/foam came out the vent on the top of the storage tank so driver shut down and they let it settle a little. Sight gauge was not reading full.   Then the sight gauge started to go down.  Driver started to offload again very slowly and sight gauge was moving up.  When tank got full, driver shut down.  Spill was wiped up with spill pad.
column169: Driver still had product left in the trailer when tank was full.  The customer thought there may be a problem with the strapping chart on the storage tank or the sight gauge.  They will check into it.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, IT WAS DISCOVERED, A CARTON CONTAINING A PAIL WAS SITTING ON TOP OF A METAL BLADE WHICH CUT INTO THE PAIL DUING TRANSIT. THE AFFECTED MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED SALVAGE DRUMS. THE DAMAGED PAIL WAS PLACED INTO A LINED SALVAGE DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME WHEN LOADING PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, PAILS, CYLINDERS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD,AND OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. PLACE CUSHION BETWEEN ROWS AND LAYERS OF CHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TO EASILY DAMAGED. TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THBOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, A 55 GALLON DRUM OF LIQUID WAS FOUND PUNCTURED AND DAMAGED BY FORKLIFT BLADE. THE DRUM AND AFFECTED MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND LINED SALVAGE DRUMS. THE DRUMS ARE BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. IF ATTACHMENTS USED FOR FORKLIFT ARE IMPROPERLY WORKING, THEY MUST BE REMOVED FROM SERVICE AND BE REPAIRED OR TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE PERMANENTLY. MAINTENANCE MUST BE DONE PROPERLY TO ENSURE SAFETY USE FOR ALL. WHEN ENTERING OR EXITING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS, OR TOTES LOADED OR STACKED ON THE FLOOR; ON A PLATFORM AND OR HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY  DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING. LEAVE PAIL OF HAZARDOUS OR CHEMICAL IN THE BAY UNTIL TRAILER IS READY FOR CLOSE. EMPLOYEE GIVEN COACHING ON LOADING AND DOCK AWARENESS.

column168: Caller reported a 3 gallon release of sulphuric acid from a tanker located at the intersection of Brunswick Ave and Allen St. in Linden, NJ.  The release seems to have originated from the dome lid as the driver noticed materials leaking down the side of the tank as well as contained within the crash box.  The leaked material has impacted an area of asphalt and no soils, storm drains, or surface waters have been impacted as a result of this release.      The driver has suspected that he may have a defective gasket.     An ERTS network contractor has been dispatched with an ETA of 45 minutes.     NJDEP has been notified and has assigned report number 080517130601 to this incident.   NRC has been notified of this release.  No incident report has been generated at this time.   It has been determined that the pressure relief valve is the cause of the release.  It seems that the aluminum flange has been damaged.     The tanker has been taken back to the shipper for repairs and reevaluation.        The contractor is utilizing sodium bicarbonate on the affected area as well as large amounts of water to neutralize the material.

column168: A BNSF mechanical rail car inspector reported GATX 13352 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the railyard emanating a residue product odor. The responders reported finding the threaded vapor valve two full turns loose and the liquid valve's closure plug one turn loose. After securement of the aforementioned, the product odor was still present. The responders detected the odor source emanating from the base flange of the liquid valve. Home shop disposition was requested for GATX 13352.

column168: At approximately 8:10pm on May 23, 2008 a minor release of Methacrylic Acid, Stabilized, 8 UN2531 occurred from a cargo tank motor vehicle.  At the time of the release the tank trailer was being delivered to an interlined motor carrier’s terminal to be stored for future transportation to a customer’s site.  Upon arrival at the interline carriers terminal, which is located approximately 1 mile from the shipper’s location, the driver observed some material being released from the rear dome of the tank trailer.  The driver immediately moved the vehicle to a safe and leveled location at the carrier’s terminal, shut off the equipment, and initiated company emergency response procedures.  An in-house emergency response crew arrived to the scene within minutes to asses the situation.  The response crew reviewed the shipping papers and determined the appropriate emergency response procedures.  Following appropriate health and safety practices the response crew utilized appropriate neutralizers and absorbent materials to clean up the released materials on the ground and the tank trailer.   All of the resulting absorbent was collected and placed into appropriate containers for future disposal at a fully license waste disposal facility.  The release of approximately 25 gallons of material was confined to the fully contained paved parking area with no offsite impact.  The clean up operation was completed by 10:00pm with no further incidents.
column169: An in depth incident review was conducted following this incident to identify the cause and determine if any corrective actions were warranted.  Our investigation determined that the tank trailer used for this shipment was a baffled trailer with three separate dome hatches for each baffled compartment.  The standard tank trailers historically used by this shipper are only equipped with one dome hatch in the center of the tank trailer.  The loaders at the site are trained to properly secure all of the tank truck opening prior to offering a shipment for transportation.  However, the loading rack utilized by the shipping location only permits safe access to the center dome and does not provide fall protection to the loaders to access any other openings.  Because the loaders could not safely access any of the domes not in the center of the trailer, the domes were not checked for proper closure.  An assumption was made that the tank trailer provider ensured that all of the tank truck openings were securely fastened prior to the tank being delivered for loading.  As a result of this investigation, the shipper will request that when possible only trailers equipped with one center dome-hatch be used for shipments from this location.  In the instances where the availability of preferred trailers is limited, the tank provider will be asked to verify and ensure that all tank trailer openings that will not be utilized by the shipper are securely fastened and secured prior to the tank’s arrival to the shipping site.

column168: Approximately 4 gallons of sodium hydroxide solution were released from a cargo tank valve, impacting an area of asphalt.  Due to rain in the area, the release was washed across a parking lot and settled into puddles of standing rain water.  No storm drains or waterways were impacted by the release.  A contractor was dispatched to the site to conduct remediation activities.  They began by pH testing the puddles and impacted asphalt.  Then the contractor utilized absorbent pads to remove the caustic rain water from the puddles and remove the material from the asphalt surface.  Once the puddles were drained, the contractor hand excavated some impacted soil from the bottom of the puddles.  After the material was removed from the area, the contractor neutralized the impacted area.  The waste was containerized for disposal and taken off site to be disposed of on a later date.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: A BNSF switch crew reported product odor emanating from entrained TCIX 21075 (DOT 111A100W5 tank car) on an outbound BNSF train that was departing the railyard. The outbound train was stopped and TCIX 21075 was carefully setout of this train and isolated in the railyard awaiting further inspection. BNSF contract responders inspected TCIX 21075 and reported that the liquid eduction valve pipe riser with a four bolt flange was leaking between the valve and the riser at the flange gasket. No suitable replacement gasket was readily available and responders secured the leakage area with flange plug at the riser and temporarily secured the valve assembly with poly-coated Tyvek tape. Contractors planned to return with a suitable replacement gasket. Spillage was neutralized with a soda ash solution. Afterwards, a shipper response team applied a new flange gasket and secured the liquid eduction line/valve assembly of TCIX 21075 making it ready for transportation. On the morning of 5/20/08, the BNSF contractor returned with a replacement gasket and discovered the TCIX 21075 had already undergone repairs.    On 5/25/08, at the BNSF North Fort Worth (TX) railyard, TCIX 21075 was again reported leaking product from the liquid eduction line/valve area. TCIX 21075 was inspected by BNSF contract responders whom reported that the four flange bolts at the liquid eduction valve pipe riser were loose and their corroded condition prevented these flange bolts to be fully tool tightened. Responders reported that the flange gasket appeared to be new and correctly applied. Spillage estimated at less than one quart product liquid was neutralized. TCIX 21075 remained isolated and motionless in the railyard until these flange bolts could be replaced. On 5/29/08, a shipper contract tank car repair response team with assistance from the BNSF contract responder replaced and properly tool tightened all flange bolts. TCIX 21075 was released to proceed to its destination after no further leakage was observed.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: The HAZMAT was a bukl load loaded on an end dump trailer.  The load was picked up at PCS Nitrogen in Augusta, GA and enroute to Austin Powder Company in Dunlap, TN.  At approx. the 164 mile marker on I-20 headed west, the driver spotted a deer in his lane of travel, which was the inside lane.  In an attempt to avoid the deer, the driver swerved to his left into the median.  When htried to return to his proper lane of travel, the tractor and trailer overturned onto the left side of the unit.  At that time, the tarp covering of the trailer failed, releasing the bulk load of ammonium nitrate.  It is unclear at this time whether or not that the weight of the material caused the tarp to fail, or if it was the abrasive action of the pavement on the tarp which caused the failure.
column169: It is reccomennded that further training be given to the drivers, and this driver in particular, on accident avoidence and emergency manuvers.  In accident avoidance, the drivers will be instructed to lower their speeds during night driving, to keep an eye out for animals in the median and shoulder of the road, and to slow down when spotted as there is an increasd chance of animals in the road when they are spotted in the median or shoulder of the road.  In emergency manuvers the drivers will be instructed to come to a complete stop if the emergency manuver places them off the roadway to reduce the chances of a rollover.  Also, the drivers will be instructed to not try to attempt emergency manuvers if presented with a similar situation, since the damage to the truck from striking an animal would be minimal verses a rollover.  Also striking an animal would be less likely to cause a rollover.

column168: On 5/14/2008 at approximately 9:30 am located at Mossy Head, FL at Lucky 13 Truck Stop MM275 EXT 70 the Land Cargo driver discovered material leaking from beneath his van trailer. The leak was small but continuous. The driver called his dispatch to report the leak. Dispatch called Univar Export Services to report that their driver had discovered a leak. The local fire department and local responders SWS First Response were contacted immediately and sent out to respond to the leak. SWS arrived on the scene at 3:40 PM and proceeded with cleanup efforts. At 4:15 pm SWS had completed the cleanup. There was no physical or environmental damage. The package had a very small pin-sized hole at the lower 3rd hoop. The drum lost 10 lbs of product so the duration of the leak was minimal and at best only about 7 or 8 hours (including the time at the truck stop). The driver created a small burm with sand until the response team arrived on scene.
column169: After carefull and detailed review of the damage to the drum in question, we have concluded that the leak was caused by operator error. The drum sustained moderate damage to the lower 3rd section at the hoop. The lower hoop was creased which in turn developed a small crack or pinhole allowing product to escape at a very slow rate. Due to improper handling of the drums while loading, the operator damaged the drum that eventually leaked. It appears that the damaged drum was struck by another drum being loaded causing moderate damage.     The operator has been properly trained and is a very experienced loader. Our team feels that the operator was in a rush to load the truck due to the heavy workload we have been experiencing.     After reviewing our drum loading procedures we determined them to be sufficient. All containers are inspected prior to loading. The inspection includes checking the van floors for nails, screws and anything that could cause damage to freight. The drums are inspected for leaks/damage/cleanliness/labeling/marks prior to loading. Upon completion of the loading process, we look for any signs of product leaks before releasing the load for transport. All vans are sealed by the loaded with a high security bolt seal. The seal number is recorded on the bil of lading.     The equipment used for the loading process are a forklift and drum handlers. All equipment used is in excellent condition. The operator has been trained to use them properly. The operator rushed the loading process which in turn directly caused improper handing of the drums being loaded.     Our response to the incident was excellent condering it's location was not near any of our facilities. We dispatched SWS First Response to perform the cleanup. After Pompano received both the damaged drum and the transfer drum, we found that 10 pounds of material was lost.    The operator shall receive refresher training on how to properly load drums on a van using drum handling equipment. The speed at which the loading is performed will also be addressed.

column168: Truck was loaded in Las Vegas, NV, destination Kingman, AZ. via E/B 163. This highway begins at route 95 and ascends 4 miles then descends 15 miles at variousgrades up to 6%. Towards the bottom the state has built a truck run away ramp. Our driver began his descent and at some point recognized his speed was to fast for conditions, he attempted to gear down in order to slow the descent however missed hisshift and the truck accelerated past the point of being able to reinsert the gear. Because the truck was not in gear the engine brake was inoperable, the drive train could not beused to slow the vehicle and only the brakes remained as a stopping device. They overheated rapidly because of the vehicle speed and weight and failed. The driverfailed to use the run away ramp and collided with 3 cars waiting at a traffic signal at the bottom of the hill. One collision broke the steering axel suspension on the truck causing the truck to turn right and rollover. The puncture in the cargo tank was caused by a large boulder and the release of cargo was instantaneous.
column169: During the investigation, it was revealed the although the driver was qualified by yearsof experience and a good safety record that he had never encountered a grade assteep as this one in equipment of this weight and configuration. Our safety process is abehavior based system and this driver was obligated to tell a dispatcher or supervisor prior to accepting the work if he was apprehensive of his ability to manage the grade;he did not. This information will be shared with all drivers at our next round of safety meetings and the truck will be been placed at all of our terminals for a brief period as a discussion generator. We have witnessed the results of this approach where the truck is now an feel it makes the largest safety impact.

The last two cars(UNPX 127502 & GMRC 23020) of a 49 car consist derailed at the # 3/4 switch point in Lawrence Yard. The derailed cars traveled approximately 1000 feet, crossing over the Andover Street Crossing when the train lost its air andstopped. When rail car UNPX 1270502 derailed at the switch point, the car struck another rail car on the adjacent track (#4 track). The opening caused a release of Sodium Chlorate (UN 1495) along track #3 until coming to a stop. Emergency response teams responded to the seen and the released material was cleaned up by a professional environmental remediation company (ENPRO).

column168: The BP company transport was traveling south on Highway I880 at approximately 2:15pm when a passing motorist waved the truck over signaling that truck had a problem. The BP driver safely pulled the truck over to the shoulder of the road, and the motorist pulled over with him. They both approached the truck and the motorist pointed out to the driver what the problem was. The BP driver found the rear compartment drop tube was leaking product from the under side. He immediately got a bucket from the trailer and put it under the leaking pipe. He then got spill pads and began laying them down around the bucket.  He then called the tech at the terminal to report the problem and ask him to call the fire department. The BP driver when back to the trailer and found a piece of wood and whittled it down to make a plug and with a spill pad pushed in the hole to stop the leaking pipe. At that time the fire department arrived and layed kitty litter down a round the bucket and used sealant putty on the leaking pipe to further stop the leaking pipe. At around 3:30pm I and two terminal employees arrived that the site. We begin draining the pipe in to two 5 gallon buckets and transferring them to gas cans. After we fully drained the drop tube we put spill pads in side the drop valve pushing them up in to the pipe were the pipe was damaged. The loaded truck was then taken to a tank shop that was less than a mile a way were the shop removed the drop pipe for repair and cap off the belly valve so the loaded tanker could be taken back to the terminal to be parked over night in secondary containment. Truck return the next day to the repair shop were the repaired pipe was put back on and the truck sent to a near by station for the delivery

column168: The freight was picked up by DSR Robert Oksness at the Billings Montana ExxonMobil Refinery and had no visible leakage at that time. Upon unloading the tote from Bob's trailer after his return to the UBG Service Center, DSR Richard Flom noticed a small amount of liquid seeping out from around the cap and collecting on the top of the tote whenever the tote was moved due to the material inside sloshing and the fact that the top cap is not properly sealed. Richard reported the leak immediately and we notified ExxonMobil of the problem. When they did not take immediate action to repair the leaking tote, we went ahead and notified Chemtrek and Nalco as well as Mike Sorensen. The tote does not leak as long as it's stationary Nalco then dispatched their local contractor who came to our location and attempted to repair the tote as well as cleaning up and disposing of the small amount of liquid that had previously leaked out. The contractors tried to tighten the cap on the tote, but upon moving it we determined that it was still leaking. They then told usthat someone from Exxon would be contacting us, as the gasket in the lid would have to be replaced or the material would have to be moved to another container.The contractors did not have an extra gasket in their posesssion. We are currently waiting to hear back from Nalco.
column169: Closer inspection of totes and bulk tanks at point of origin prior to filling them with product. This tote should've been removed from service prior to this becoming a problem.

column168: Severe back pressure in NL tank bubbled up out of spill containment about twenty  gallons. Driver arrived at the store and stuck the tank at 37 inches (3178 gallons) in a 12,000 gallon tank. He was supposed to drop 3900 NL. He hooked up his vapor recovery then started his 2800 gallon compartment. About 10 to 15 minutes into the drop the hose jumped as if the tank was full. The driver shut down the product and  then noticed that product was bubbling up from the Spill containment area. It filled the spill containment area and started to run out onto the concrete. He tried to contain spill with spill pads but product kept bubbling up from spill well. He walked the hose down to assure it was empty and wanted to cap the tank to try and stop the product from flowing out of the tank. He removed the fittingwith the hose still attached, when he did the gas from the tank sprayed. He got the cap onto the tank but product was still coming out of the tank. By this time the fire department showed up and took over the scene. They sprayed foam over the area and onto the soil behind the drop without having a barrier to stop any of the gas water or foam. The tank had plenty of room for the entire 3900 nl to fit but would not take even 2800 nl. There is no reason why this tank would have this kind of back pressure especially if there was more that 4800 gallons of room before 90%.

column168: A SHIPMENT OF “CHARCOAL” WAS DISCOVERED ONBOARD J078/O1MAYO8, KANSAI JAPAN TO HONOLULU, HI. AWE: 131 5070 5653, 1P/7. 2KGS, SHIPPER: WAKABAYASHI MFG. CO., CNEE: NICHIREN MISSION OF HAWAII THE SEQUENCE IS AS FOLLOWS:  01MAY08 — 0930 — QUESTIONED THE COMMODITY OF “CHARCOAL” 01MAY08 - 1208 — SENT TTY MSG TO JAPAN TO CONFIRM IF THIS IS A DANGEROUS GOODS OR NOT, BASED ON THE COMMODITY. 02MAY08 — 0942 - SENT EMAIL TO JAL’S HEAD OFFICE TO INVESTIGATE. 05MAY08 — 1000 - CLEARED U.S. CUSTOMS, SEC321. 07MAY08 - 1436 - RECEIVED EMAIL FROM JAL’ S HEAD OFFICE, SHIPMENT IS INFACT A DANGEROUS GOODS, A REPORT WILL BE SUBMITTED TO JCAB. O8/O9MAY - LEFT MSG WITH FAA RICHARD GILES/WESTERN-PACIFIC REGION REGARDING OUR INTENTION TO VOLUNTARILY DISCLOSE A DANGEROUS GOODS VIOLATION. 13MAY08 - 0630 - CONTACTED FAA MIKE GIVENS AND ADVISED OUR INTENTIONS. 13MAY08 - 0930 - MET WITH FAA TONY TEPEDINO AND DISCUSSED THE SPECIFICS OF THE SAID VIOLATION. 13MAY08 - COMPLETED DOT FORM F5800.1 SHIPMENT OKAYED BY FAA TONY TEPEDINO TO DELIVER TO CNEE. PHOTOS TAKEN AND AWB GIVEN TO FAA TONY TEPEDINO.
column169: DANGEROUS GOODS TRAINING AT JAL CARGO IN HNL CONSISTS OF A SECTION ON HIDDEN DANGEROUS AND KNOWLEDGE OF COMMODITIES. CHARCOAL IS A COMMODITY THAT IS USED AS AN EXAMPLE DURING TRAINING THEREFORE IT WAS EASILY IDENTIFIED. WITH TRAINING COMES KNOWLEDGE, WITH MISTAKES COMES EXPERIENCE. TO IMPROVE OUR KNOWLEDGE OF  DANGEROUS GOODS, TRAINING (KNOWLEDGE OF THE ENGLISH LANGUAGE MAY BE LACKING), EXPERIENCE (IF WE CAN LEARN BY OUR MISTAKES AND SHARE INFORMATION). SINCE THE IRREGULARITY ORIGINATED UPON ACCEPTANCE IN JAPAN AND THE COMMODITY WAS TYPED IN  ENGLISH, IT SEEMS ACCEPTANCE STAFF DID NOT RECOGNIZE OR QUESTION THE COMMODITY. IN FUTURE THE ACCEPTANCE STAFF SHOULD MAKE ALL EFFORT TO UNDERSTAND THE ENGLISH WORD SO COMPLETE UNDERSTANDING OF A COMMODITY MAY BE ACCEPTED. (USE OF A DICTIONARY, COMPUTER, “GOOGLE IT”, ETC.)

column168: Police say around 8:00 a.m. Friday, May 23, the truck was traveling along Appling Road when two of its wheels veered off the pavement. The driver over-corrected, causing the truck to overturn at Appling and Southern Way. The truck was carrying 8,500 gallons of unleaded gas. Gasoline escaped from the dome cover on one compartment. Approximately 500 gallons were released to the roadway: the remaining gasoline on the truck was transferred to another truck. The driver was not hurt in the accident.    TN EMA contacted - assigned Mission No. 44.    Other than using absorbents and a vacuum truck to contain and remove gasoline from the roadway and the truck there was minimal additional remediation.  No additional environmental work is anticipated.    Rescue crews from Bartlett, Memphis and Shelby County responded to the scene. Residents of "King's Daughters and Sons Home" were evacuated as a precaution. The facility provides rehabilitation services for disabled senior citizens. There are 104 patients who live at the facility, 80 of which are wheelchair-bound. The patients were taken to the Bartlett Recreation Center.

column168: FILE- 08-31 FAA SHIPPER- SAGRES AGENCIAMENTO MARITIMO LTDA AWB#- PDA 6704784531 HOU    ON 05/18/2008 AT 0959, A LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED IN "F" BUILDING, LOCATED AT THE DHL ILN MAIN SORTFACILITY, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. SPILL TECHNICIANS CECEILA HICKEY AND MATTHEW GROSVENOR DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE. THEY REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. column168: Freight appeared to have been punctured with the pallet that it was stacked on brioke, causing the release of product.  Due to the amount & type of material released, a qualified emergency response contractor was used to handle clean up & containment.
column169: Release was due to no fault of the shipper as the pallet that it was loaded on broke & the broken slat punctured the bag.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: ONE GALLON CAN TURNED OVER IN THE CARTON AND THE LID POPPED OFF.  RELEASING ABOUT 1/2 GALLON OF PAINT.  LID PLACED BACK ON CAN AND REST OF FRT WAS SENT ON TO THE DESTINATION. The shipper actually used a box that was made for 4 1-gallon cans but they only shipped it with 3 cans and tried to fill the   void space with shredded paper. The can fell over during transit into the void space resulting in the lid popping loose and the small spill.
column169: Correct packing of the materials by the shipper would have prevented this spill.

column168: Plant Operator was preparing to unload rail car to trailer. Upon hooking up liquid line to the “B” side, Operator observed release of vapor. The Operator immediately identified the leak at the locking nut, and shut everything down. The Operator reported the incident to his immediate supervisor, who was on site. The supervisor checked the valve and found that the packing nut was loose. The packing nut was tightened, and lubricant was applied to the stem. This was successful in stopping the leak. 10 pounds of vapor was estimated to have been released. No evacuations were made, No injuries were reported and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: The drum was noticed leaking from the bottom. Investigation revealed a small cut in the drum from a nail sticking up from the loading surface. The drum was placed in a recovery receptical and will be disposed of according to all local and federal regulations. No further action is needed.
column169: Cardboard should be required to be placed under any drum loaded on skids. This will reduce the likelyhood of this type of release. Cardboard also cushions the drums and reduces movement and shock.

column168: The drum was punctured by the operators fork blade causing the release from the bottom of the drum. The material was covered with clay replacement and rendered neutral. The release was managed in 2 hours. No further actions are required.

The employee was treated at an emergency room for skin irritation and released.  Tom Robinson, Manager of Hazardous Materials, was notified and advised he was  en route. G.A. Rodrigue, Occidental Chemical, advised shipper  personnel would be dispatched for repair and remediation.  At 12:10 PM, Tom Robinson, Manager of Hazardous Materials advised the  tank car had six of eight manway swing bolts less than tool tight. column168: At 02:24 PM on 5-9-08, Frank Lerch, Manager Hazardous materials was contacted by the RMCC, and advised the following. Rudolf   Hill, Manager of Yard Operations, reported a train crew had observed an unknown amount of gasoline leaking from the top of tank car   TILX 318779. Car was entrained on train MAVBT 08, Lead Locomotive CN 2626, at the Beaumont railyard at Beaumont, TX., Mile Post   281.00 of the Lafayette Subdivision. Car was located 25 cars back from the head end of the train. All personnel were clear of the area   and no drains or waterways were being impacted from the release.   Check of waybill information indicated car to be loaded with   Gasoline, Flammable Liquid, UN1203. Upon being notified, Mgr. Lerch responded and requested the shipper be notified via   Chem-Trec. While enroute Mgr. Lerch spoke with Torn Hunt, Production Supervisor for Westlake Petrochem, advising him of the   leaking car. Mr. Hunt indicated that he woUld bc responding.   Upon arrival and inspection of the car, Mgr. Lerch noted product   leaking from an open sample line needle valve within the combination housing. Additionally, the needle valve plug was lying on the flanged and bolted manway cover plate. Upon closing the needle valve, and screwing the plug into the needle valve, the car was secured from further release. Less than 10 gallons had been released onto the ground, which pooled below the car. With the use of absorbent material the spill was contained, and site remediated. On arrival of Westlake Petrochem personnel, additional absorbent material was utilized with the remediation. The car was then released to continue onto destination without further incident. Original protecting seal combination housing WLGROUPo0054783, replaced with UPRR CTS 0008698.

column168: Kerry Douglas, Manager Yard Operations, reported a strong chemical odor was detected on Departure Track 305 of the Livonia rail yard. Mr. Douglas advised there were no reports of exposures, injuries, or inhalations. Mr. Douglas advised tank car UTLX 649610, a load of styrene monomer, had sloshed from the top of the railcar, with some product on the side of the tank, with a limited number of drops on the ground with no pooling noted.   Torn Robinson, Manager Hazardous Materials, responded and inspected the tank car.   This inspection revealed that the sloshing of material and dripping onto the ground was do to humidity condensing onto the tank car and not styrene. A small amount of styrene was leaking from the base of the 2-inch quarter turn ball valve, where the valve threads onto the liquid line nipple. This material was evaporatinG before t could run dowi the side of the tank car. Robinson conferred with Mr. Larry Huffine of Chevron Phillips and U.S,E.S.; a response contractor was dispatched to assist Robinson. The tank car was relieved of vapor pressure and the liquid valve was removed. The threads of the nipple were wrapped with Teflon tape and the valve was reinstalled. This secured the tank car from leaking. Shipper Chevron Phillips secured movement approval, FRA-08050139, and re-billed the tank car back to the St. James plant.

FLIGHT NUMBER GT603 // 31 MAY 08 // AIRCRAFT TAIL # N499MC. Aircraft departed HSV enroute to PIK.Through SATCOM operations (approximately 45 minutes after departure) the crew reported a strong chemical odoron the aircraft. Aircraft was diverted to JFK. Airport Authority and Fire Department officials met the aircraft at the end of the runway and found nothing on the aircraft which the HAZMAT team could identify as hazardous to the crew.All tests came back negative. Aircraft was released back to crew. Atlas JFK station personnel notified ChemTrec.Minute Man Spill Response team suited in proper PPE and unloaded the pallet and did not find any visible spill orleak. As stated in Minute Man Spill report they did not pick up any readings on meters that were above normal. Theyfound a potential cause for the odor in a 20 gallon keg / drum that had a separation at the top where the bungattaches. This was not a shipping failure but a packaging imperfection. The product was Furful Alcohol Toxic 6 andthe product would be consistent with the odor described by the flight crew. The technicians also identified insectsattracted to the keg. The separation could be enough to allow the odor to escape but not have a visible spill. Also didnot get any reading on meters and the meters would not pick up a toxic odor. This is consistent with the fire department in that they also did not get readings even in the confined space of the aircraft. The keg was placed into a 30 gallon over pack drum, sealed, and labeled. The over pack would seal any vapor and prevent any potential spill.In the over pack drum the keg was safe for shipping. The keg was shipped back to HSV via truck transport.
column169: As per Minute Man Spill response report "this is not a shipping failure but a packaging imperfection".

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was in transit between the shipper’s location and the intended waste management disposal facility.   During a routine stop at Clean Harbor’s Braintree, MA Transfer, Storage and Disposal Facility, the material was transferred into an alternate vehicle for continuing transportation.  At the conclusion of the loading operation, the driver noticed that 2 containers had developed a small leak at the bottom chime of the containers.  It is estimated that approximately 3-5 gallons of material had released onto the floor of the van trailer with approximately ½ gallon of material leaking onto a concrete lined containment pad.  Facility personnel immediately enacted the facilities emergency response plan and using appropriate personal protective equipment entered the trailer and placed both containers into suitable salvage drums.  All free liquids were absorbed with a suitable absorbent material and this was placed in the salvage drum along with all material used to decontaminate the floor of the van trailer.  In addition, all material that was released to the containment pad was cleaned up and all debris placed in the salvage drums.  Once cleaned, the two salvage drums were sealed and we placed back onto the vehicle for continued transportation to the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time of loading, the containers were inspected and no evidence of leaking was observed.  The driver along with all loading personnel involved have been instructed to insure that a thorough inspection is performed and any containers of questionable integrity is placed into a suitable salvage drum prior to accepting for transportation.

column168: THE LEAKING RAILCAR WAS DISCOVERED BY A CONTRACTOR EMPLOYEE THAT WAS DRIVING BY AT 09:26. HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OUR COMPANY'S EMERGENCY DISPATCH. UPON ARRIVAL IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THERE WAS A LEAK NEAR THE SUMP OF THE RAILCAR. THE DURATION OF THE LEAK WAS JUST OVER 10 HOURS. SAN BERNARDINO COUNTY FIRE AND THE DOT WERE NOTIFIED, AND WERE ON-SITE FOR THE DURATION OF THE INCIDENT. IT WAS UNCLEAR TO SAN BERNARDINO COUNTY FIRE HAZ-MAT AND THE DOT INSPECTOR ON-SITE AS TO THE ACTUAL CAUSE OF THE LEAK. AN EMPTY RAILCAR WAS PLACED NEXT TO THE LEAKING RAILCAR. KEMIRA (AN ON-SITE TENANT) PUMPED THE LEAKING RAILCAR'S CONTENTS INTO THE EMPTY RAILCAR. FILTER RECYCLING'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM CONTAINED A PORTION OF THE LEAKING ACID, BY LACING A CONTAINMENT POOL UNDER THE LEAK. THE CONTENTS OF THE CONTAINMENT POOL WHERE THEN PUMPED INTO TOTES. AFTER THE ACID TRANSFER WAS COMPLETE, FILTER RECYCLING WELDED THE LEAKING RAILCAR. THESE MEASURES EFFECTIVELY STOPPED THE RAILCAR FROM LEAKING. AFTER GAINING APPROVAL FROM BOTH THE NOT AND SAN BERNARDINO COUNTY FIRE HAZ-MATE, THE RAILCAR WAS MOVED TO A SECURE LOCATION ON THE FACILITY. PICTURE ATTACHED.

column168: Tankcar GATX 30311 was releasing product from the top of the car by the Multi-Housing. Upon investigation, the liquid valve was found to be partially open, and the valve plugs less than tool tight. All other fittings were secure on the car. The valve was closed, and the plug tightened by representatives of Hulcher Services. The car was then released for continued transportation.

GB. Reeder received a call of a strong, pungent odor. An inspection of the track indicated NATX 75140 was leaking from the top. Liquid was seeping from the base of the liquid valve. The valve was also partially open. The valve was closed, the valve itself tightened, and the pressure relieved from the car. The plug in the air line was also loose. No remediation was necessary as the product readily evaporated once the release was stopped.

column168: During outbound train make-up in the railyard, a BNSF crew member reported an ammonia odor emanating from one of the railcars in the switch movement. The movement was stopped and all crew members vacated the area. This area was cordoned off until a detailed inspection could be initiated by hazardous material responders. During the inspection by BNSF contract responders, GATX 201247 (DOT 112J340W tank car) was found with product odor emanating from the threaded connection where the sample line valve's pipe nipple threads into the pressure plate. The responders applied putty around this threaded connection which eliminated the product odor. GATX 201247 was monitored and no further odor was detectable and the internal pressure within GATX 201247 was holding constant. Railyard operations were resumed at 0020 hrs. CDT, 5/28/08. In the morning of 5/28/08, the same contract responders successfully applied a Midland Sample Valve Capping assembly over the sample line valve to eliminate any product emissions. GATX 201247 was again monitored and no product detection registered on the responder's air monitoring devices.   FRA Movement Approval MA-08050163V was received to transport GATX 201247 a short distance back to the shipper facility for unloading.

First report was that load shifted and caused driver to loose control of tractor and trailer fliping it on it's side and sliding for 800 feet before coming to a stop. All absorbants and recovery agents were used by Emergancy reponse people and fire department to contain the area.  Clean Venture was called in to clean up the area and recover product.
column169: We have a annual training class on hazmat each year, and had an additional hazmat and drivers meeting following this accident. We have installed a triple check system to ensure that each load is check 3x's before leaving, to ensure it is properly secured and placard before making any deliveries. We have discontinued to use this shipper and have stream lined how we will move such freight going forward.

column168: Russell Kelly, Federal Railroad Administration Hazardous Materials Inspector observed tankcar TILX 190874 with product on the sides of the car. Mr. Kelly notified Leon Hendrickson, Manager of Hazardous Materials. Leon Hendrickson, responded and confirmed tankcar TILX 190874 had released approximately 10 gallons of diesel fuel that was contained to the top and sides of the railcar. The release occured because of a defective safety relief valve. The car was repaired and decontaminated at the Union Pacific Provo Utah Yard. The shipper obtained a one time movement approval. The car was released for transportation.

column168: A BNSF roadswitcher departing the railyard derailed seven railcars near and under the Ambassador Caffery Parkway overpass. The cause of thisderailment is still under investigation. GATX 72822 (DOT 111A100W5 tank car) derailed leaning into the overpass concrete support abutmentstructure. This collision impact resulted in the top safety handrails collapsing into and shearing off the vapor valve of GATX 72822. Product releasedfrom the open orifice vacated by the vapor valve and ceased once product equilibrium within the leaning tank car was reached and also after GATX72822 was uprighted. Lime was applied to neutralize ground spillage and impacted soils were excavated and sent to an approved landfill fordisposal. Later, site restoration was completed. The remaining product in GATX 72822 was transferred into tanker trucks by 0850 hrs. CDT, 5/18/08and returned to the shipper. GATX 72822 was cleaned and purged afterwards on 5/18/08. Air monitoring and soil samplings were maintainedthroughout the duration of this event.A precautionary evacuation of one mile radius was initiated which impacted approximately 3000 people. The evacuation ended at approximately1830 hrs. CDT, 5/18/08. Also, during railcar rerailing activities, a six mile span of U.S. Interstate 10 was closed and traffic rerouted. This closureended around 2100 hrs. CDT, 5/17/08 after a duration of approximately two hours.
