column168: Shortly after GATX 50162 (DOT 111A1OOW5 tank car) was switched in the railyard, an inbound BNSF local crew observed and reported GATX50162 leaking product. GATX 50162 was carefully moved and isolated at the east end of the railyard. BNSF and contract responders discovered a small (1/4 inch) corrosion hole at the bottom of the sump area of GATX 50162. An internal rubber lining failure was suspected. Responders inserteda shaped boiler plug with caulking into the hole to stop the product release. A fiber glass resin was also applied over the outside plug area as an additional seal. The product leak was stopped by approximately 2000 hrs. CDT, 5/28/08. The ground spillage was contained within a dirt berm that was built and spillage was neutralized with lime. The neutralized ground spillage was remediated. The remaining product inside GATX 50162 was transferred into another suitable tank car without incident by 0530 hrs. CDT, 5/29/08. Soda ash was then poured into GATX 50162 to neutralize any product heel left inside this tank car.The Omaha F.D established an isolation area of 500 ft. around GATX 50162. An evacuation was initiated that impacted approximately 100 homes ina 1/2 mile area in south Omaha. This evacuation included Rosenblatt Stadium where a minor league baseball game was in progress which impacted approximately 2500 spectators and participants. Also, the Henry Doorly Zoo evacuated a group of students visiting the zoo. The U.S Highway 275 bridge over the Missouri River was also closed to vehicular traffic and the Omaha police discouraged traffic within a square mile of the spill site. The evacuation and road closures were lifted at approximately 0440 hrs. CDT, 5/29/08.

column168: Shipment left Origin (Lake Charles LA) containing 135 pieces (96 pails, 39 boxes) on May 15,2008, on trailer 313-7100, changing trailers in Abilene, TX, and Portland Or, arriving at destination on May 21,2008. Shipment was unloaded and notated as damaged at that time. Shipment was loaded on trailer 313-5238, and secured for delivery to customer. Delivery driver Paul Cranfill, broke his set of trailers and headed directly to Carboline. When he opened his door at Carboline, he immediately noticed that the rope used to secure the freight had broken and the pallet of pails were leaning onto another pallet.Driver Cranfill proceeded to search for leakage on the leaning pails, and noticed some seepage on the bottom of the pallet. With the help of Carboline Driver Cranfill started removing the pails to investigate further into where the leakage was coming from. Once all the pails were removed, it was determined that a total of 3 pails were leaking, and 45 were dented. They were immediately placed into a salvage drum. Upon futher investigation Driver Cranfill noticed that this pallet had to have been recouped previously, because there were rubber gloves tossed inside the pallet, and the pallet was wrapped in cardboard .Driver cranfill then cleaned the leaking product also placing it in the salvage drum, and returned the salvage drum and the 45 refused pails back to our dock in Fife.

column168: A voltage regulator was removed from a substation and transported to an in-house Hazardous Waste Storage Facility for disposal. The regulator was shipped in accordance with the liquid polychlorinated biphenyl special provision #81 as identified in 49 CFR 172.101, "Table of Hazardous Materials and Special Provisions." Special provision #81 states that a polychlorinated biphenyl item, itself, may be used as packaging if it meets the general packaging requirements of 49 CFR 173 subparts A and B. Prior to transportation, the regulator met the general packaging requirements and showed no signs of leakage.The regulator traveled from a substation in St. Cloud, MN to Minneapolis, MN. Approximately six blocks from arrival,the driver noticed that oil was leaking from the top of the regulator and dripping down the side. Due to the small amount of oil observed on the side of the unit, the driver decided it would be best to continue to the delivery location rather than stop in the middle of the city street. It is estimated that the release lasted three-five minutes.Upon arrival at the delivery point, the regulator was brought indoors and the PCB contaminated oil was immediately pumped out of the equipment. Xcel Energy employees walked the route back to determine the extent of the release.A trail of oil, mainly small spots every few feet, was observed back to the off-ramp the driver used to exit the Interstate (see attached map for route info). There was no free product in the roadway that needed containment, as the oil was only spotty and had already soaked into the asphalt, (continued on attached sheet)
column169: Oil filled electrical equipment that will be transported from field locations will have the oil pumped into a cargo tank in the field and will be shipped empty whenever possible. If for some reason pumping the oil into a cargo tank is not possible, or practical, drip pans and transformer bags will be used whenever transporting PCB contaminated electrical equipment, whether it is leaking at the time it is to be transported or not. This should contain any oil theelectrical equipment may leak while in transit due to a faulty component.

column168: On May 19th, 2008, during a cargo transfer to unload a damaged/leaking package (i.e. a non-regulated/non-hazardous commodity)from a shipper sealed freight container, it was discovered inside two cylinders labeled as containing UN1001, Acetylene, Dissolved; and UN 1072, Oxygen, Compressed, respectively. After review of the offeror's shipping papers, it was determined that these two commodities/packages were actually undeclared hazmat.    Upon this discovery, the two cylinders were removed from the freight container and immediately rejected for transport. Thus, the shipper was notified immediately that there shipment failed to meet our conditions of acceptance, and therefore, would need to be removed from our terminal facility or be made compliant for transportation. The result was the shipper elected to rescind the request for us to accept and transport their shipment, and the shipper picked up said shipment soon thereafter.    NOTE: On May 23rd, 2008, The shipper (Laparkan Trading) submitted an OHMS Incident Report on this same incident. However, it became apparent at a later date that this did not satisfy our own obligation to meet the HMR requirements; thus, the reason for this late submittal.     /// END OF REPORT ///
column169: Recommend increased community outreach programs specifically focused on informing the low-volume hazmat shippers of the HMR; Increase number of DOT HAZMAT workshops held annually and increase the number of locations where they are held.    /// END ///

column168: ICTF Security reported a released of product from lM Tank BLKU 251560, while being inspected in Lane 2 at the Inbound Gate of the ICTF, Long Beach, CA. Dean Cooper, Manager, Hazardous Materials was notified and advised he was on site. Mr. Cooper stated inspection and testing of the liquid was Ph neutral. At 07:54PM, Manager Cooper advised further inspection of the manway noted approximately three gallons of product had been released due to a bad manway gasket. The gasket had been crimped when the manway cover was secured, and approximately 12 inches of the gasket was inside the manway nozzle, rather than on top of the nozzle rim. Manager Cooper stated the product on the cement was remediated, however, the manway gasket would require replacement by the shipper. An attempt was made to notify Cal Specialties Americas, Emergency Shipper Conthct, as listed on the waybill. The office hours of Monday through Friday, 8:00 AMto 5:00 PM, Eastern Time, was provided via recorded message, and notification was unable to be completed. Manager Cooper contacted APL, UP’s shipper of record, and was advised the’ would contact Bulk Haul, Houston, Texas, and advise them of the required repairs. On Wednesday, May 21, 2008, representatives from Ventura Lezbro, local IM repair contractor, arrived on site and replaced the damaged manway gasket. The IM Tank was then released for movement onto the consignee.

column168: Describe the sequence of events that led to the incident and the actions taken at the time it was discovered. Describe the package failure. including the size and location of holes, cracks, etc. Photographs and diagrams should be submitted if needed for clarification. Estimate the duration of the release, if possible. Describe what was done to mitigate the effects of the release. Continue on additional sheets if necessary.   A pickup truck, owned by l-Iarwichport Heating and Cooling, collided into a tractor and tank trailer, owned by Cape Cod Oil, at the intersection of Great Western Road and Lothrop Avenue in Harwich, MA. The accident was caused by the driver of the Harwichport Heating and Cooling vehicle’s failure to stop at the stop sign at the Lothrop Avenue/Great Western Road intersection.   As a result of the accident, the tractor and tank trailer rolled over, rupturing the front compartment (3,400 gallon capacity) and rear compartment (3,500 gallon capacity) of the tank. A total volume of approximately 3,800 gallons of #2 fuel oil was released to the roadway and shoulder surfaces as a result of the incident.   Response actions have included: Pumping of remaining fuel oil inside of the tank, closure of the public road and bike path, the placement of sand berms, deployment of absorbent pads and booms, use of vac trucks to remove oil from the road surface and standing water in the wetland, removal of oil impacted vegetation from the wetland water line, placement of a harbor boom to prevent the migration of oil on the surface water table, excavation and off-site disposal of contaminated soils, groundwater recovery and treatment, and chemical oxidant injections to treat residual groundwater impact.
column169: Where you are able to do so, suggest or describe changes (such as additional training, use of better packaging, or improved operating procedures) to help prevent recurrence. Provide recommendations for improvement to hazardous materials transportation beyond the control of your individual company. Continue on additional sheets if necessary.   The accident was caused by the driver of the Harwichport Heating and Cooling vehicle’s failure to stop at the stop sign at the Lothrop Avenue/Great Western Road intersection. Cape Cod Oil Company was not found to be at fault in the accident.   Cape Cod Oil Company’s training prodecures, packaging, and operating procedures were found to be fully acceptable by all authorities involved.   No recommendations for improvement by Cape Cod Oil Company were identified.

column169: PHMSA REPORT NO. 08462028 INDICATES SHIPPER WAS CHARGED WITH 6 VIOLATIONS OF 49 CFR REGULATIONS AND INDICATES THAT LETTERS OF CORRECTIVE ACTIONS WERE ISSUED TO THE SHIPPER WITH CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN BY THE SHIPPER. THESE VIOLATIONS INCLUDE: 1) FAILURE TO PROVIDE THE CARRIER WITH A COPY OF SPECIAL PERMIT DOT-SP 11186; 2) FAILURE TO INCLUDE SPECIAL PERMIT NUMBER ON THE SHIPPING PAPERS IN ASSOCIATION WITH THE SHIPPING DESCRIPTION; 3) FAILING TO PROVIDE ADDITIONAL INFORMATION ON THE SHIPPING PAPERS AS REQUIRED BY 49 CFR I.E. ONE-WAY-TRAVEL-TIME (OWTT) AND THE TANK'S PRESSURE AND AMBIENT (OUTSIDE) TEMPERATURE PRIOR TO SHIPMENT; 4) OFFERING FOR TRANSPORTATION, IN COMMERCE, A PORTABLE TANK IN AN UNAUTHORIZED OR DAMAGE/DEFECTIVE STATUS I.E. ALL EMERGENCY DEVICES OF THE PORTABLE TANK WERE CONFIRMED TO BE DEFECTIVE AT TIME OF OFFERING AS PER TEST RESULTS PROVIDE IN THE WENDELL HULL & ASSOCIATES REPORT NO. WHA08H127; 5) OFFERING FOR TRANPORTATION A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WITH IMPROPER MARKINGS ON THE PORTABLE TANK; AND 6) FAILING TO PROVIDE FUNCTION SPECIFIC TRAINING TO ITS EMPLOYEES CONCERNING THE REQUIREMENTS CONTAINED IN THE SPECIAL PERMIT.    VESSEL ISM PROTOCOL REVIEWED BY RO AND REPORTED TO USCG. POST INCIDENT REIVEW AND SAFETY TRAINING GIVEN TO CREW REGARDING STEVENDORING INCIDENTS AND HAZMAT INCIDENTS ON BOARD VESSEL. OCEAN CARRIER COMMENCES USE OF NATIONAL CARGO BUREAU TO MAKE A REVIEW OF THE DANDEROUS CARGO MANIFEST ON A PER VOYAGE BASIS. THESE INDEPENDENT REVIEWS CHECK FOR STOWAGE AND SEGREGATION COMPLIANCE WITH BOTH IMDG AND 49 CFR REQUIREMENTS AND INVOLVE INTERFACE WITH PORT CAPTAIN AND CHIEF OFFICER PER PORT CALL AT PEV. ANY EXCEPTIONS NOTED BY THE NCV DURING A REVIEW ARE CORRECTED PRIOR TO TIME OF LOADING.    THERE IS REASON TO BELIEVE THAT LETTES OF CORRECTIVE ACTIONS WERE ISSUED BY OSHA TO THE STEVEDORING COMPANY.

column168: Passenger Armando DeSantiago was questioned about his use of oxygen when the flight attendant noticed he was using a nasal canula during flight (DL1566/22MAY LAX-ATL).  Once it was determined Mr. DeSantiago was using a liquid oxygen device (Companion 550), the device was secured from Mr. DeSantiago by the On-board leader and he was provided on-board emergency oxygen bottle.  The Delta Operations Control Center contacted the Emergency Management Duty Officer for guidance.  The flight proceeded to ATL. Delta ensured the device was emptied in ATL and liquid oxygen was not transported for additional flight legs. Mr. DeSantiago was advised of the device being prohibited on passenger aircraft and medical oxygen was ordered for all remaining flight legs.

Forklift radiator hose busted and started squirting out radiator fluid-driver jumped off forklift without stopping unit and forklift punctured tote of paint pigment. This took place   on dock of the Albuquerque, NM terminal. Advance Environmental Solutions, Inc.  was contracted to handle this spill including cleaning and waste removal of product.  Upon receiving the final report from AES, we question whether or not they had reported this spill.  The reponse from the manager is that they never report any spill as required unless they have a free standing contract with a company or if it involves an Interstate. At that time I notified the Local office of the DOT and asked for advicee. Advance Environmental Solutions, Inc. 2318 Roldan Dr. Belen, NM 87007 AES Project No: E-8149  ph# 505 861 1700

column168: On May 2, 2008, Picked up a nurse tank of Anhydrous Ammonia at Farmers Mill & Elevator, Inc. Hetowed the cargo tank with his own vehicle to his field farm property next to his shop building located at 22595 Cedar Ave, Farmington, MN 55024. The tank was left next to the shop overnight. On Saturday, May 3rd, 2008, Was at the shop all day and did not notice any leakage. Returned Sunday, May 4th to theshop and also did some mowing. When he left at 3:30 PM the tank was not leaking. Arrived an hour later at 4:30 PM and by then emergency personnel were on the property.
column169: Employees at Farmers Mill & Elevator, Inc. have been reminded to check & double check all valves on anhydrous equipment.

column168: FILE- 08-97 DOT SHIPPER- LARRY AULL AWB#-AHN 51362377846 IND  ON 05/13/2008 AT 2112 EST, A LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED AT THE NORCROSS DHL EXPRESS STATION, LOCATED AT 955 NORCROSS INDUSTRIAL COURT, NORCROSS, GA 30071. ED FROM THE NORCROSS STATION REPORTED THAT THEY HAD A LEAKING LAB OVERWRAP SHIPMENT THAT WAS CONTAINED TO THE BOX. MANAGEMENT ADVISED SHIPMENT COULD BE DOUBLE BAGGED AND A SALVAGE DRUM WOULD BE SENT. THIS SHIPMENT WAS FOUND TO BE A FIBERBOARD BOX  CONTAINING A ZIPLOC TYPE PLASTIC BAG WITH AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF A BIOLOGICAL SUBSTANCE CATEGORY B INSIDE. DUE TO THE SHIPMENT BEING DAMAGED DURING TRANSIT, A TOTAL OF .05 LITERS OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST.  THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO NORCROSS DHL EXPRESS STATION VIA TRUCK #4233.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS MARKED AS UN3373.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 2119 EST.  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

column168: FILE- 08-23 OMC SHIPPER- JAMES KOLLAT AWB#- YNG 68522321744 SLC ON 05/20/2008 AT 1524, A LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED IN “F” BUILDING, LOCATED AT THE DHL SORT FACILITY, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. SPILL TECHNICIANS WILLIAM HENDERSON AND BILLI MARSH DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE. THEY REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR   INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION, THEY FOUND THIS SHIPMENT 12 X 12 OZ METAL AEROSOL CANS OF Ri 2 REFRIGERANT. THIS DID NOT LEAK, BUT WAS NOT DECLARED AS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO WILMINGTON VIA TRUCK # 6045. THIS OUTSIDE OF THE SHIPMENT WAS NOT DECLARED AS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, HOWEVER, THE INNER FIBERBOARD BOX WAS MARKED/LABELED AS DICHLORODIFLUOROMETHANE, CLASS 2.2, UN1028.
